    scripture: { verse: "Be still and know that I am God.", reference: "Psalm 46:10 (NKJV)" },
    prayer: "Lord, on this day of reflection I am still before You. Thank You for every step taken this week — even the imperfect ones. You are God, and You are working in me. I rest in that today. Amen.",
    content: `You have made it through your first week. Before you rush to week two, stop. Be still.

God built rest into the rhythm of creation. The Sabbath was not a reward for productivity — it was written into the fabric of existence from day seven of creation. Rest is not laziness. Rest is obedience. It is an act of trust that says, "I do not have to keep striving to be worthy."

**Review Your Week**

Look back at this past week with curiosity, not judgment. Ask yourself: What did I learn about my eating patterns? When was I most connected to genuine hunger? When did I eat emotionally, and what was the underlying feeling? What small win can I celebrate?

Celebration matters. Your brain releases dopamine when you acknowledge progress — making it more likely to repeat the behavior. Don't wait until you reach a goal to celebrate. Celebrate the noticing. Celebrate the pause. Celebrate choosing water. Celebrate asking "why am I eating this?" even if you ate it anyway.

**Release Perfectionism**

If you missed a day, had an emotional eating episode, or skipped a lesson — none of that disqualifies you. This is not a program you pass or fail. It is a journey you take one day at a time.

Lamentations 3:22-23 reminds us: "His mercies are new every morning." Every single morning is a fresh start. Not when you've earned it. Not when you've been good enough. Every morning. Freely. New.

**This Week's Reflection Questions**

1. What was the biggest "aha" moment from this week's lessons?
2. Which lesson was hardest to apply, and why?
3. What is one thing I want to carry into next week?

Rest today. You do not have to earn your next breath.`,
